'''Selma Bajrami''' (born 4 July 1980) is a popular [[Bosnians|Bosnian]] [[pop-folk]] and [[turbo folk]] singer of [[Bosniak]] and [[Albanians|Albanian]] ancestry.

Some of her career hits are "Kakvo tijelo Selma ima", "<U+017D>ena sirena" and "Tijelo uz tijelo".

==Early life==
Bajrami was born in the summer of 1980 in [[Tuzla]], then a part of [[SFR Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]] and presently in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia]]. Her father Fadil (born 1957) is an [[Albanians|Albanian]] who moved to Bosnia in 1965 from the town of [[<U+0110>akovica]] in south western [[Kosovo]], while her mother Enesa (born 1960) is a [[Bosnian Muslim]] from the town of Tuzla. Selma has a sister Fahira (born 1977) and brother Enes (born 1984).<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N0Sn0d6MaSU&feature=related|title=Selma Bajrami @ Biseri|publisher=YouTube|date=|accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref>

==Career==
Selma began her career at the age of fourteen in 1994, singing with a band in [[kafana]]s and bars during the [[Bosnian War]].

Her first album, ''[[Kad suza ne bude]]'', was released in 1998 through the record label [[Nimfa Sound]] and contained multiple hit songs "Nije moja majka kriva", "Ho<U+0107>e dragi da me <U+017E>eni", "Sta <U+0107>e <U+017E>ena ta", "Kad suza jednom ne bude", "Ne ljubi me", "Da li da se kajem", "<U+017D>elje moje, pusti snovi", "Moj si samo kad ti trebam", "Njemu osmijeh, meni suze", "Za<U+0161>to boli kad se voli", "I ja lutam i ja patim" and "Svi<U+0107>e dan" (which was later covered by [[Serbs|Serbian]] singer [[Ceca (singer)|Ceca]]). The album was, for the most part, written and composed by [[Mili<U+0107> Vuka<U+0161>inovi<U+0107>]].

Bajrami's second album was produced by Mi<U+0107>a Nikoli<U+0107>. This album, titled ''[[Ljubav si ubio gade]]'' (1999), included a few hit songs: "Daleko od o<U+0107>iju, daleko od srca", "I Bog je sa nama", "Pijanico", "<U+017D>ivot lije<U+0107>i rane", "Mrva hljeba", "Lutkica", "Ko je kome ostao du<U+017E>an", "Moj golube" and the title track.

Her third album ''[[Revolucija]]'' was released in 2001 and featured the songs "Idi od mene", "O<U+0107>i zelene", "<U+017D>iva zdrava", "Ne mogu te voljeti", "Hajde <U+017E>ivio", "Nije vi<U+0161>e 18 meni", "Otvori se zemljo" and "Svi ste vi isti". It was produced by Dejan Abadi<U+0107> and took on a different sound from her previous albums. 

''[[<U+017D>ena sa Balkana]]'' (2002) was her fourth album. With hit songs such as "Nano", "<U+0160>korpija", "Grijeh i molitva", "Svi mi ka<U+017E>u", "<U+0160>ta da ti dam", "Ne mogu da te volim", "<U+017D>ena sirena", "Ne mogu bez tebe", "Bi<U+0107>e<U+0161> moj" and the title track, Selma gained even greater popularity than before. The song "<U+017D>ena sirena" ([[English language|English]] translation: ''[[Siren (mythology)|Siren]]'') became Selma's nickname.

The songwriters of her fifth album, ''[[Kakvo tijelo Selma ima]]'' (2004), included Dragan Brajovi<U+0107> Braja, Dragi<U+0161>a Ba<U+0161>a and Nanin from [[Tuzla]]. The song "Ljubavi jedina" was written by Selma herself. This album was the second one produced under Dejan Abadi<U+0107>.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://selmabajrami.net/|title=Oficijelne web stranice Selme Bajrami|publisher=SelmaBajrami|date=|accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref> ''Kakvo tijelo Selma ima'' included five hit songs including the title track, "Tijelo uz tijelo", "<U+017D>alim", "Divlji zov" and "Mu<U+0161>ka suza".

Her sixth album, ''[[Ostrvo tuge]]'' was released in 2007 through the record label [[Grand Production]] (owned by [[Lepa Brena]]) and included the hit songs:"Lijepe <U+017E>ene", "Boli me no<U+0107>, boli me dan", "Malo se poigraj", "Promjeni se", "Korak do nervnog sloma", "Davno si ubio ponos u meni", and the title track.

Bajrami's seventh album was called ''[[Selma 2010]]'', released in spring 2010, included the hit songs "Farmerice", "Nemoj da se <U+0161>ali<U+0161>", "Bak<U+0161>i<U+0161>", "Sarajevo", "Pamtim", "<U+0110>avolica", "Zakon sudbine", "Nije zlato sve <U+0161>to sija" and "Voli me do bola".

She is currently recording her eighth studio album to be released near the end of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.svetplus.com/vesti.asp?vid=23183|title=Povratak Selme Bajrami: Novi singl D<U+017E>ejms Din (Video)|publisher=SvetPlus|date=15 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref> The first single off the album is called "James Dean" (named after [[James Dean|the American actor]]). A 20-second preview of the song was released on [[SoundCloud]] on 30 November 2012,<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://soundcloud.com/adis-pez/selma-bajrami-james-dean|title=Selma Bajrami - James Dean preview|publisher=SoundCloud|date=30 November 2012|accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref> while the full song was released on [[YouTube]] on 14 December 2012.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_embedded&v=4BvIEtJUb0o|title=Selma Bajrami - James Dean|publisher=YouTube|date=14 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref> The song was originally titled "Djevojke" (English: ''Girls'').

==Personal life==
Bajrami met her second husband Mujo Musi<U+0107> in July 2011, during a performance of hers on a boat on the [[Modrac Lake]] in Selma's birth city of Tuzla.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.azramag.ba/cafe/3854-selma-bajramii-i-mujo-music-mujce-za-koga-se-udaje-zena-sirena.html|title=Za koga se udaje <U+017D>ena Sirena?|publisher=azramag|date=2 December 2011|accessdate=21 April 2013}}</ref> The were wed on 22 December 2011 in front of 100 guests at the hotel Tuzla in the same city, having only been engaged a month.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.svetplus.com/vesti.asp?vid=13916|title=Udala se trudna Selma Bajrami|publisher=SvetPlus|date=23 December 2011|accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref> Her first marriage, in 2003, ended in divorce.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.dodirnime.com/zanimljivosti/udala-se-selma-bajrami/|title=Udala se Selma Bajrami|publisher=dodirnime|date=24 December 2011|accessdate=21 April 2013}}</ref>

She moved with her second husband to his home in [[Vienna, Austria]] with a pregnancy due date of 4 July 2012, her 32nd birthday.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.kurir-info.rs/selma-bajrami-nosi-musko-clanak-291119|title=Selma Bajrami nosi mu<U+0161>ko?!|publisher=kurir-info|date=26 June 2012|accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.pulsonline.rs/puls-poznatih/13741/tanja-savic-i-selma-bajrami-postaju-mame-istog-dana|title=Tanja Savi<U+0107> i Selma Bajrami postaju mame istog dana?!|publisher=PulsOnline|date=1 July 2012|accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref> She gave birth via [[caesarean section]]<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.expressmag.ba/top-news/5066-ekskluzivno-selma-bajrami-na-craski-rez-rodila-sina.html|title=Ekskluzivno: Selma Bajrami na carski rez rodila sina!|publisher=ExpressMag|date=11 July 2012|accessdate=21 April 2013}}</ref> to a baby boy named Daris seven days later than expected on 11 July 2012 in Vienna.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.vesti-online.com/Scena/Estrada/239050/Selma-Bajrami-rodila-sina|title=Selma Bajrami rodila sina|publisher=VestiOnline|date=13 July 2012|accessdate=22 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.folk-estrada.hr/exkluzivno-selma-bajrami-izvela-sina-darisa-u-setnju-foto/|title=EXKLUZIVNO: Selma Bajrami izvela sina Darisa u <U+0161>etnju! (FOTO)|publisher=Folk-Estrada|date=10 September 2012|accessdate=10 September 2012}}</ref>

